cs.CR, cs.SE, cs.DC, cs.AR, cs.PL

The paper discusses controlled-channel attacks on trusted execution environments (TEEs) and proposes a new attack called CopyCat that can accurately reconstruct enclave control flow at a maximal instruction-level granularity. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper discusses vulnerabilities in cryptographic libraries and proposes novel algorithmic attacks for key extraction, which further supports the classification of the paper under cs.CR. The paper also involves discussions on the architectural interfaces and microarchitectural resources, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-categories of Software Engineering (cs.SE), Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC), Computer Architecture (cs.AR), and Programming Languages (cs.PL). However, since the focus of the paper is primarily on security and cryptography, cs.CR is the most likely sub-category.
